8. Further: Even if the Law be unjust as to its Matter and Ob- Ject, and oppressive to the Subject3 for example, an unnecessarily heavy tax, the Obligation is not destroyed necessarily. We must here distinguish between what is merely unjust suffering, and what is immoral doing. If the thing commanded be of the former kind,—-an iniquitous infliction, not a wicked act in the sufferer,—the fault is in him who gives the command. It is no crime to obey3 it is 3, fault not to obey.

But if the thing commanded be morally bad, the doing it is a sin in both parties,--him who commands, and him who obeyS.

And thus, the meaning of our Conclusion is, that Human Laws

which prohibit what is morally necessary, or command what is morally unlawful, do not bind the Conscience.
